library(corrr)

corrr is a package dedicated to working with, manipulating, and visualizing correlation matrices.

Iris data

iris_corrr <- iris %>% 
  purrr::keep(is.numeric) %>% 
  corrr::correlate()
## 
## Correlation method: 'pearson'
## Missing treated using: 'pairwise.complete.obs'

Contrast this with the behavior from cor() function from base R.

iris_cor_base <- iris %>% 
  purrr::keep(is.numeric) %>% 
  cor()

The long-format is especially useful for working with grouped correlation dataframes. Letâs create the grouped correlation dataframe for each level of Species.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Species, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf)

We can now visualize the correlation coefficient with ggplot2 using facets to display the levels of Species.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Species, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r),
            color = 'white') +
  facet_wrap(~Species) +
  labs(x = '', y ='') +
  theme_bw()
## 
## Correlation method: 'pearson'
## Missing treated using: 'pairwise.complete.obs'
##

Modify the correlation plot fill and legend.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Species, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r),
            color = 'white') +
  facet_wrap(~Species) +
  scale_fill_gradient2('corr',
                       low = 'indianred2',
                       mid = 'white',
                       high = 'skyblue1',
                       midpoint = 0,
                       limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(x = '', y ='') +
  theme_bw()

I like to dispaly the correlation coefficient as text or to annotate the plot.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate, quiet=TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Species, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r),
            color = 'white') +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = r)) +
  facet_wrap(~Species) +
  scale_fill_gradient2('corr',
                       low = 'indianred2',
                       mid = 'white',
                       high = 'skyblue1',
                       midpoint = 0,
                       limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(x = '', y ='') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=0.5))
## Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values (geom_text).

The corrr package has a helper function called fashion() to make the text display âprettyâ. I prefer to use the base R round() function to round the value.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate, quiet=TRUE, diagonal=1)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Species, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r),
            color = 'white') +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = round(r, 2))) +
  facet_wrap(~Species) +
  scale_fill_gradient2('corr',
                       low = 'indianred2',
                       mid = 'white',
                       high = 'skyblue1',
                       midpoint = 0,
                       limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(x = '', y ='') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=0.5))

  purrr::keep(is.numeric) %>% 
  correlate(quiet=TRUE) %>% 
  network_plot(legend = FALSE)

Lastly, letâs calculate the correlation matrix per group of Class.

Sonar %>% 
  group_by(Class) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate, quiet=TRUE, diagonal=1)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Class, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r), color='white') +
  facet_wrap(~Class, labeller = "label_both") +
  scale_fill_gradient2('corr',
                       low = 'indianred2',
                       mid='white',
                       high='skyblue1',
                       midpoint=0,
                       limits = c(-1,1)) +
  labs(x='',y='') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=0.5))

Use string manipulation from the stringr package to extract the number for the variable.

Sonar %>% 
  group_by(Class) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = purrr::map(data, correlate, quiet=TRUE, diagonal=1)) %>% 
  mutate(cor_lf = purrr::map(cor_wf, stretch)) %>% 
  select(Class, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(x_number = stringr::str_extract(x, "\\d+"),
         y_number = stringr::str_extract(y, '\\d+')) %>% 
  mutate(x_number = as.numeric(x_number),
         y_number = as.numeric(y_number)) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = as.factor(x_number), y = as.factor(y_number))) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r), color='white') +
  facet_wrap(~Class, labeller = "label_both") +
  scale_fill_gradient2('corr',
                       low = 'indianred2',
                       mid='white',
                       high='skyblue1',
                       midpoint=0,
                       limits = c(-1,1)) +
  labs(x='',y='') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=0.5))
